  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There have been several significant legal precedents in money laundering cases. Some key examples include:\n\n1. United States v. Bank of New England (1985)\n- First major case establishing bank reporting requirements\n- Set precedent for corporate criminal liability in money laundering\n\n2. United States v. BCCI (1991)\n- Large international bank convicted of widespread money laundering\n- Highlighted cross-border financial criminal activities\n\n3. Bank Secrecy Act cases\n- Established regulatory frameworks for financial institutions\n- Required suspicious activity reporting\n\n4. Basel Committee recommendations\n- International standards for anti-money laundering protocols\n- Set global guidelines for financial transparency\n\nThese are general legal precedents. For specific detailed legal analysis, I recommend consulting a legal professional who can provide authoritative guidance.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these examples or discuss money laundering legal principles more broadly?",
